  "buggy_functions": ["azx_resume"],
  "confidence": 0.95,
  "reasoning": "The HDA Intel driver has state variables 'polling_mode' and 'poll_count' that track fallback modes when codec communication times out. These variables are set to non-zero values when timeouts occur (lines 912 and 898-904 in azx_get_response). However, during suspend/resume cycle: (1) azx_stop_chip() sets chip->initialized=0, (2) azx_resume() calls azx_init_chip() which reinitializes the hardware, (3) but polling_mode and poll_count are never reset back to 0. This causes the driver to persist in polling mode after resume, leading to choppy audio and timeouts. The chip structure is zero-initialized on initial probe (kzalloc in azx_create), so polling_mode and poll_count start at 0, but after a suspend/resume cycle where timeouts occurred, these variables retain their non-zero values. The fix requires resetting polling_mode=0 and poll_count=0 in azx_resume after azx_init_chip() but before snd_hda_resume() to ensure the driver starts fresh after resume."
}

